I'm so glad that I made it to the gym so early in the morning. Did shoulders and legs. This is one of my favourite shoulder workout. I would usually lift it all the way up, but being preggers, any overhead workout is discouraged. 
Be sure to keep your back straight and your glutes tight. You can lean back slightly to work the quads as well. Since my arms are hyperextend, I keep my elbows micro-bent. I'm lifting a 5kg plate. 15reps x 3sets.

Surprise surprise: I look super excited with my cake here right? However, the irony is that I left as one disappointed Paris Baguette customer because the Square (the name of this cake) I tried got so terrible in the span of just one week?! The first time I tried I found it delightful light and tasty, like eating whipped sugar. If you like whipped cream, this would have been right up your alley - floating sugar dancing a romantic waltz down your palate and the strawberries a squirt of zesty flavor that complements it perfectly. BUT horrors of horrors, the night we tried this the cream was clumpy and the cake was ALMOST STALE and awfully dry. How can the quality control plummet so abysmally over the period of a week? Unbelievably disappointing - it was Ben's first time trying (my second) and never again 😡
properties.sentiStrings: disappointed terrible clumpy STALE Unbelievably disappointing 😡

Ramadan is not about giving up bad habits temporarily. Ramadan is about starting point to become a better Muslim and give them up for good.
Not a month of temporary religiousness. So for example If a person tends to read the Qur’an more often in Ramadan, then he should maintain habit even after Ramadan.
A woman might only wear her hijab for Ramadan and she is criticised for it and deemed a hypocrite, or
someone might be attending the masjid more often for Ramadan and is criticised for only doing it in Ramadan. We think this kind of attitude towards so called Ramadan-Muslims is unfair and discouraging. Why not recognise the efforts people are making and over look their bad habits? If someone is trying to make a difference, be it only for Ramadan, why not encourage them that they may continue their efforts throughout the year?
We hope people realise that saying more good things, increasing ones prayer and good actions etc in the month of fasting is at least a good thing. And good things should be encouraged 🍃🍂 #MukmininYouthAmbassador #masjidalmukminin #ramadanreminders

Ramadan is a special time of year -- a time when Muslims around the world take a step back from their daily routines and focus on community, charity, fasting, and prayer. Is there a family in your neighborhood that you haven't seen in a while?  A student in a strange new city?  A new Muslim who is fasting for the first time?  An elderly couple who can't get to the mosque?  Why not take a few minutes to make a phone call, drop in for a visit, or invite someone to iftar (dinner to break the daily fast). Even the smallest gesture of kindness can make a huge difference in someone's life. Most importantly, during this very special month, take the time to pray for others - your family, your loved ones, those who are ill, those who live in fear, those who go hungry, those who walk in darkness.  May Allah guide all of us upon the straight path of faith, and help us to be filled with piety, patience, humility, and kindness. #masjidalmukminin #mukmininyouthambassador #ramadanreminder
